---\nAutomate portions of the pull request review process to improve efficiency and maintain quality. The following steps should be taken to set these automations up:\n\n## Tasks:\n1. **Linting and Code Quality**\n   - Configure CodeQL for static analysis.\n   - Set up linters (e.g., ESLint, Flake8, RuboCop) in GitHub Actions workflows.\n\n2. **Automated Tests**\n   - Ensure unit, integration, and end-to-end tests are implemented.\n   - Set up CI pipelines to execute test suites automatically for every PR.\n   - Integrate code coverage tools like Codecov or Coveralls.\n\n3. **Pull Request Review Bots**\n   - Explore bots like Reviewpad, Danger.js, or Reviewable to automate checks (PR descriptions, size, changelogs, etc.).\n\n4. **Semantic Analysis for Documentation**\n   - Integrate tools like Vale for enforcing content style guidelines.\n   - Explore AI tools for refining user-facing text (e.g., tone, grammar consistency).\n\n5. **Custom Automation Scripts**\n   - Write scripts for validating URLs, enforcing naming conventions, or generating reports (e.g., glossary updates).\n\n6. **Checklists and Templates**\n   - Enhance PR templates with automated checklists.\n\n## Expected Outcome:\nBy implementing these automations, the review process should:\n- Reduce manual workload for reviewers.\n- Ensure consistent code and documentation quality.\n- Streamline the process for faster PR approvals.\n\n## Next Steps:\n- Assign this task to a DevOps specialist or team member experienced with setting up GitHub workflows and automation.\n- Review existing tools/workflows in the repository to identify gaps.\n\n---